  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying Without Genuine Innovation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Startup Visa requires an innovative product or service. Traditional freelancing, consulting, or generic businesses don't qualify. Be honest about whether your concept involves genuine innovation—if not, consider Latvia or Estonia's options instead.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">No MVP or Prototype</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Just an idea isn't enough. You need a Minimum Viable Product or functional prototype. The authorities want to see that you've actually built something, not just have a business plan.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 120-Day Company Registration</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After receiving your Temporary Residence Permit, you must register your company within 120 days. This is a strict deadline—missing it can invalidate your residence status. Start the registration process immediately upon arrival.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Insufficient Runway</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While there's no minimum income requirement, you need sufficient funds for self-sufficiency. Plan for at least 6-12 months of expenses. Authorities may question your application if your financial situation seems precarious.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Weak Innovation Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The authorities review your business plan and prototype carefully. Vague descriptions or unclear innovation won't pass scrutiny. Be specific about what makes your solution innovative and different from existing alternatives.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

