  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does Lithuania have a digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not exactly. Lithuania doesn't have a dedicated DNV like some EU countries. The closest option is the Startup Visa for tech entrepreneurs with innovative products. Traditional freelancers may use the National D Visa for self-employment, though it's more complex.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What counts as "innovative" for the Startup Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Innovation typically means technology-based solutions, novel products, or new approaches to existing problems. SaaS, fintech, AI/ML, healthtech, and cleantech usually qualify. Traditional services, consulting, generic e-commerce, or dropshipping don't meet the innovation requirement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there a minimum income requirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Lithuania's Startup Visa has no minimum income requirement—unique among EU options. However, you must demonstrate sufficient funds for self-sufficiency. Having 6-12 months of expenses saved is recommended.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I have to register a company?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. After receiving your Temporary Residence Permit, you must register your company in Lithuania within 120 days. This is a strict requirement—failure to register can invalidate your residence status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can the Startup Visa lead to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Continuous legal residence in Lithuania can lead to permanent residency application. The Startup Visa provides a pathway to long-term settlement, and eventually citizenship (typically after 10 years, or 5 with integration requirements).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How's the startup ecosystem in Vilnius?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Vilnius has a growing startup ecosystem, particularly strong in fintech. Resources include Vilnius Tech Park, Startup Lithuania (government support), multiple coworking spaces, and regular tech events. The community is international and welcoming to foreign founders.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

